===Verb===
'''vituttaa'''

# (''profane'') The word ''vituttaa'' is one of a few Finnish verbs that in their basic form already describe an on-going thing, and can include the person experiencing the thing. ''Vituttaa'' means roughly "is deeply annoyed" or ''pissed off''/''to piss off'' (literally "it cunts"), and if no other person is indicated, in most cases it applies to the user of the word. 

*The on-going status of annoyment is called [[vitutus]].

*Derived from [[vittu]].

*Some females may like to use the word ''[[kyrpii]]'' instead. 

*Often replaced by ''hatuttaa'' which rhymes with vituttaa, literally: It hats.

===Examples===

#''Mua vituttaa!'' means "I'm deeply annoyed!" Literally: It cunts me!
#''Mua vituttaa aivan kyrpänä!'' Literally: It cunts me like a cock.
#A Finn can go and meet a friend, and just say the one word, ''vituttaa'', to communicate their annoyment.

;Words with similar properties
''[[panettaa]]'' "is craving to fuck" derived from ''[[panna]]'' "to fuck"

''hirvittää'' "is horrified". Derived from ''hirveä'' "horrible".

''korpee'' Literally: "it deserts", a mix of ''[[kyrpii]]'' and ''[[korpi]]'', used in the sense of being annoyed.

